"c647100" == c647100  <c647100@showme.missouri.edu> writes:

c647100>   Please explain. Surely you would allow that I can take the
c647100> action of wishing you a nice day merely by posting it? Or of
c647100> challenging you to a duel? 

Certainly, but that is because those actions are naturally
communicative in nature, and thus emitting a communication is the act
inherent in performing them.

c647100> And if certain game events were contingent on those actions,
c647100> that I could trigger them by doing so? 

I do not contest the use of communicative acts as possible triggers
for consequential events.

c647100> Now let's extend the situation. Let us assume a particular
c647100> commodity is owned by various Players but there are no Rules
c647100> that specifically allow or disallow trading them.  I don't
c647100> see any problem, in principle, in allowing such trades in the
c647100> absence of the Rules. It merely involves the free desires of
c647100> the Players. You may not wish them to have the power, but
c647100> that can be resolved by passing a Rule, not by summarily
c647100> restricting their freedom of action.

I have no problem with allowing the unrestricted trade of unregulated
commodities.  But I do have a problem with equating the expression of
the desire to trade commodities with the trade itself.  I can post,
until my fingers are raw from typing, that I am sending $5 to Chuck,
without ever causing Chuck to receive any money.  All I have done is
expressed a desire.  But a desire, no matter how fervently expressed,
remains only a desire until and unless it is actualized by some
concrete action.  We are not gods, or djinni; we cannot cause reality
to change merely by desiring it to do so.

This has nothing to do with "not wish[ing] them to have the power",
but merely recognizing that no such power exists.  The power you refer
to is a fantasy; it does not exist.  Your model devolves to
omnipotence for everyone, the power to actualize any wish, and is thus
clearly ridiculous.  And I submit that you will be unable to establish
suitable limits that avoid conflicts with physical reality and still
retain the abstractual power you wish to assert, or at least will not
be able to do so without creating a conceptual structure so complex as
to be unwieldy for the purpose of playing a game.  (Yes, I have tried.)

c647100> Similarly, I think Players should be allowed to make
c647100> enforceable Contracts in the absence of a specific Rule, or
c647100> of forming legal Groups for that matter.

Contracts, yes.  Enforceable, no.  There is no basis in the Game
Contract for such enforcement.  Again, Chuck and I could enter into a
contract of some sort.  Suppose I were to breach it.  Chuck could call
a CFJ on the question as to whether I had breached the contract, and
the CFJ might be judged TRUE.  But the Judgement places no compulsion
on me to abide by the breach clauses of the contract, or make
restitution for my breach, because no Rule requires me to abide by
the contract I enter into.

Of course, if Chuck were to prosecute the matter in the Monroe County
Circuit Court, or the Federal District Court for the District of
Southern Indiana, a compulsion could be created by a judgement of the
court.  But that is because both Indiana and American federal law
recognize the common law of contracts (as modified by the Uniform
Commercial Code, to which Indiana subscribes, and other pertinent
state and federal statues).  Agora does not.  Nor should it, since the
common law of contracts is somewhat variable from country to country,
and Agora's playership derives from at citizens of least seven
different countries.

c647100> I mean no disrespect, but you seem preoccupied with what is
c647100> "physically possible", when we are dealing with abstract
c647100> entities that are subject to no natural law. 

No, we are not; your statement indicates that you fail to understand
my position entirely.  I am not in the least bit concerned with
abstract entities, nor do I believe that we are at all dealing with
them.

c647100> Many games allow actions that in real life would be
c647100> impossibilities.

I believe you are being disingenious here.  What really happens is
that these games allow for actions which, by consensual agreement, are
considered to be symbolic of actions which are physically impossible.
The physically impossible actions remain impossible; the players
merely agree to pretend as though they had taken place anyway.  Some
games, especially role playing games, are entirely or nearly entirely
encapsulated by such consensually agreed-upon symbolisms.  I do not
believe that Agora is such a game, however.  Agora is firmly imbedded
in the real world, and I think it should stay there.

c647100> I'm not sure that deriving authority for such actions from a
c647100> specific Rule(s) that lists specific procedures under
c647100> specific circumstances is any more implausible, inane, or
c647100> silly than deriving authority from a general Rule that lists
c647100> none of the above. 

The general Rule you suggest is contrary to natural law; it asserts
that Players can fly by declaring it, for example, when we know that
they cannot.


