Scott sez:

> Laurent> What sort of problems do you envision that would make it
> Laurent> impossible to reconcile Nomicness with the essential aspects
> Laurent> of a RPG ?
> 
> The Rules have to be changeable, and the Rules are in the real world;
> if you completely push everything into a fantasy world, there's no way
> to change the Rules.

I'm afraid I don't follow the inference. Fantasy worlds also have rules, don't
they ? (In fact entire fantasy novels are constructed on this premise, notably
Jack L. Chalker's delightful Dancing Gods saga, which I recommend.) In fact,
most RPGs have at their core rule books which regulate how purely abstract and 
communicative actions on the parts of the players "project" (are symbolic of, 
to use your own phrase) to make-believe 'events' in a fantasy world.

My contention is that it would be quite feasible to construct a fantasy world
in which the rules contained in such rule books would have a fantastic
counterpart in whatever world the game was set in; and to have those rules
contain provisions that allowed symbolic, make-believe 'events' in such a
fantasy world result in rule changes. (These 'events' would after all 
correspond to perfectly ordinary acts in the physical world, such as the 
throwing of dice or communicative exchanges between Players.)

To be sure, it would be possible, given the possibility of changing the Rules,
to modifiy the actual rules in such a manner that the symbolic rules would get
out of sync, or that it became impossible to modify one or the other set. But
then again, Agora could be mutated in a non-Nomic by similar processes; my
point is that I see no obstacle to establishing a one-to-one, bidirectional
relationship between fantasy rules and actual rules, such that it would be 
possible (with suitable 'suspension of disbelief') for players to pretend that 
the characters they manipulate were themselves changing the rules of their own 
world.

The challenge in such a game would be to frame the language of the rules in 
such a way that it would not shock the players out of that suspension of 
disbelief and be consistent with the fantasy setting used; a medieval fantasy 
for instance would have to avoid terms such as 'email' or 'print media'. But 
then again, this is only an issue of obtaining the appropriate consensus from 
players participating in the game, or, if you will, the appropriate meta-rules 
concerning the use of language.

